## .NET 8 Migration

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET 5+
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — catching it is dead code
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
            var completed = _workerTask.WaitAsync(
                timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

            try
            {
                await completed;
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Log warning — worker didn't stop in time.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort().
                // You must ensure all blocking calls accept
                // the CancellationToken so they can be interrupted.
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Expected during cancellation
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort()` replacement. You **must** make every blocking call cancellation-aware via `CancellationToken`. If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Socket`/`DbCommand`/`BlockingCollection`, pass the token or it will hang on shutdown. |
| **Sync-over-async traps** | If you can't go fully async, use `CancellationToken` with synchronous APIs: `collection.Take(token)`, `stream.Read(..., token)`, `handle.WaitOne(timeout)`. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile bool` can't interrupt a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` cooperatively interrupts waits, polls, and async I/O. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | It compiles but never executes. If your rollback logic lived there, it silently disappears. Move it to `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` crashes at runtime** | Not a compile error — it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime. Easy to miss without tests. |

### If You Must Keep Synchronous Code

```csharp
// Wrap a non-cancellable blocking call with a cancellation-aware shim
private WorkItem GetNextItemSync(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        if (_queue.TryDequeue(out var item))
            return item;

        // Poll with short sleep instead of indefinite block
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(millisecondsTimeout: 100);
    }

    throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
}
```

**Bottom line:** The core migration principle is replacing **forced termination** (`Abort`) with **cooperative cancellation** (`CancellationToken`). Every blocking call in the processing loop must accept and respect the token, or graceful shutdown is impossible.
